etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in John Bale (1495–1563), bishop of Ossory, evangelical polemicist, and historian. From gad + -er

definitions: A person who gads or gads about; (now especially) one who goes to many social events or travels to many places for pleasure; a gadabout.

etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in The Manufacturer and Builder. From gad + -er

definitions: A machine designed to drill a straight line of holes in rock, used in the process of breaking up and removing rock from its bed.
